<p>
<seg id=1> At the same time, the Chinese and the local Indonesians were guarding their houses shoulder to shoulder around Chinatown at Jakarta, the capital of Indonesia. </seg>
<seg id=2> Chinatown has suffered another attack of violence since the serious riot and revolt in May. </seg>
<seg id=3> Please listen to another report by VOA reporter Grant from Jakarta. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> As night fell, the soldiers were firing warning shots to disperse the young men who flung stones at the police at Leto in the Chinatown area. </seg>
<seg id=5> Several hours ago, some thousand people gathered in groups and burned a bank less than a kilometer away from the Presidential Palace, and the fire soon spread to the nearby shops. </seg>
<seg id=6> This group of young men used a lamppost to knock open the doors of the shops. </seg>
<seg id=7> During the attack on the Chinese on Saturday, a group of men dragged a Chinese to the street and beat him up, and then dumped him into a ditch. </seg>
<seg id=8> Later the soldiers drove out an army-carrying car and rescued this seriously injured person. </seg>
<seg id=9> Tanks were patrolling on the streets covered with stones and broken glass, and thousands of soldiers with guns and tear bombs were guarding the local business districts to keep the mob away. </seg>
<seg id=10> The businessmen who ran electrical appliances there were forced to move their shops elsewhere since the revolt in May. </seg>
<seg id=11> The reporter saw a 29-year-old young man surnamed Min standing on guard behind a wired blockade, who had only a pair of pants on tighteded with a belt. </seg>
<seg id=12> This young man working in a computer company said that he and his Muslim neighbors were guarding there overnight to prevent the mob from robbing their houses. </seg>
<seg id=13> Mr Min said that his neighbors had built this wired blockade since the May revolt, but they had never realized it would be put to use so soon. </seg>
<seg id=14> At some places where blockade was established, the local residents carried big sticks to disperse groups of strangers. </seg>
<seg id=15> A resident named Darsiat wore a Muslim hat and a Muslim sarong. </seg>
<seg id=16> He told the reporter that most of those young robbers hurried here from beyond Chinatown after hearing of the riot taking place here. </seg>
<seg id=17> The mob robbed and destroyed a subway station a kilometer away; when the soldiers chased them, they threw away their shoes, computers and clothes-hangers, which were strewn all over the road. </seg>
</p>
